@NODE Description

@{B}Description@{UB}

ZX DataType is a picture datatype for displaying Sinclair ZX Spectrum
pictures under Amiga OS release 3 or higher.

Why would someone need a picture datatype for Spectrum screens? I don't
know... I just created it for fun. I liked the idea of being able to view
Spectrum pictures with MultiView, or having them inlined in a WWW page.
Kinda neat, don't you think? :-)

ZX DataType recognises several different file formats.

 - Raw SCREEN$ image. Length is 6912 bytes.

 - SCREEN$ file saved with the ZX Interface 1. Length is 6921 bytes.

 - SCREEN$ file in the ZX82 (Amiga Speculator) format. Both compressed and
   uncompressed (length is 6924 bytes) are supported.

 - SCREEN$ file saved on the +D and ported to the Amiga using ReadPlusD.
   Length is 7396 bytes.


@{B}Usage@{UB}

You can use MultiView, or one of the dozens of picture viewers that support
datatypes, to view a ZX Spectrum picture on your Amiga. You can even use
programs like Personal Paint or ImageFX to edit one.

I've included some ZX Spectrum pictures for your viewing pleasure in the
'Pictures' directory.


@{B}Requirements@{UB}

Release 3 or higher of the Amiga operating system is required.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation

@{B}Installation@{UB}

Installation can easily be performed by running the included 'Install ZX
DataType' installation script. Below are the instructions for doing the
installation by hand.

@{B}1.@{UB} Copy the file 'Classes/DataTypes/zx.datatype' to the directory
'SYS:Classes/DataTypes'.

@{B}2.@{UB} Copy the file 'Devs/DataTypes/ZX' and its '.info' file to the directory
'DEVS:DataTypes'.

@{B}3.@{UB} Activate ZX DataType by double-clicking its icon or by executing the
Shell command 'AddDataTypes REFRESH'.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Transferring

@{B}Transferring@{UB}

There are two ways that I know of for transferring SCREEN$ pictures from a
Spectrum to the Amiga.

 @{" The ZX Interface 1 method " LINK "The ZX Interface 1 method"}	This is what I used.

 @{" The Plus D method " LINK "The Plus D method"}		This is what Gerard Sweeney uses.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "The ZX Interface 1 method"

@{B}The ZX Interface 1 method@{UB}

If you own a Sinclair ZX Interface 1 then you can tranfer files via a null
modem cable using the RS232 port. This is the cable I used.

ZX Spectrum          Amiga 500   or   Amiga 1000
Interface 1

    1   ..............  1  ............ no connection
    2   ..............  2  ............  2
    3   ..............  3  ............  3
    4   .............. 20  ............ 20
    5   ..............  5  ............  5
    7   ..............  7  ............  7

You could use the following BASIC program on the Spectrum to save out the
screen. It loads a picture from tape and then saves it to the serial port.

  10 LOAD "" SCREEN$
  20 SAVE *"b" SCREEN$

On the Amiga side you need a terminal program with capture capability. Way
back in 1990 I used ATalk III. You'll have to set the parameters to 9600
baud, 8 data bits, 1 stop bit and no parity. Simply open a capture file with
no text filtering before sending the screen, and close the capture file
after completing the transfer. It should take about 10 seconds. If all went
well, you should end up with a file that is 6921 bytes long. The extra 9
bytes are the file header.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "The Plus D method"

@{B}The Plus D method@{UB}

A brief word on how to transfer +D SCREEN$ files to the Amiga.

You need:-

1. A speccy
2. A +D
3. An Amiga
4. ReadPlusD by Peter McGavin.

I don't know which version of ReadPlusD it actually is, as there isn't a
version string available. I do know that the file itself is 17240 bytes in
size.

I got this version from Dalmation BBS, where the Sysop got it directly from
Peter himself, so I don't know if it's available anywhere else but I think
Peter released it with a bunch of other stuff on Aminet a while back....

So to business... Just save the screen you want on the speccy using the +D's
built in saver (pressing 3 if you're slow hehe).. This will save a snapshot
off on the +D which is a SCREEN$ type.

Then put the disk into the Amiga and use ReadPlusD using READPLUSD
[diskdriveno] [snapno] [Amiga filename]. This will create a filename which
is 7396 bytes long. You can now use Multiview on this to save it as an IFF.

As I'm absolutely hopeless at programming in Arexx or any other language, I
found the best way to do batch conversions was using DOpus and the cool util
DT2IFF by Marcus Hillenbrand, and have a button or menu set with:-

AmigaDOS DT2IFF {f} t:  [or whatever dir you want the IFF to go to]

Do all files
No filename quote


You can then just highlight the pics you want converted, and take it from
there...


I hope this is clear enough for you. If not, you can reach me on
GSS@ARTS.GLA.AC.UK.

Thanks,
Gerard Sweeney
Hackers Anonymous
Team Amiga

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ARexx script"

@{B}SaveSCREEN$.zxam@{UB}

SaveSCREEN$.zxam is an ARexx script for ZXAM (the ZX Spectrum emulator by
Antonio J. Pomar Rosselló) to save the Spectrum's screen to a file for
viewing with ZX DataType.

If you install it in the 'ZXAM_Rexx/English' directory of the emulator, you
will be able to call it from the 'Run ARexx' button in ZXAM.

When you run the script, you will be presented with a file requester for
entering a name for the SCREEN$ to be saved. The extension '.zx' is
automatically appended if not already present.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Release history"

@{B}Release history@{UB}

Version 39.3 released 24-Nov-1996

 - Now supports SCREEN$ files which have been saved on the +D and ported to
   the Amiga using Peter McGavin's ReadPlusD. Requested by Gerard Sweeney.

 - Added chapter on using @{"the Plus D method" LINK "The Plus D method"} for transferring piccies from
   the Spectrum to the Amiga. Provided by Gerard Sweeney. Thanks Gerard!

Version 39.2 released 2-Nov-1996

 - Now supports ZX82 (Amiga Speculator) files with compression. Requested by
   Simon Goodwin.

Version 39.1 released 10-Oct-1996

 - ZX Spectrum SCREEN$ pictures don't have to end in '.zx' any more to be
   recognised.

 - SCREEN$ files with the ZX82 header are now recognised. Requested by Simon
   Goodwin.

 - The best screen mode ID is now calculated instead of simply using LORES.

 - Included extra picture, 'Commando86.zx'. Supplied by Simon Goodwin.

Version 39.0 released 23-May-1996

 - First public release.

ZX DataType is based on a program called ZXscreen that I wrote when I first
got by Amiga 500 in 1989. Version 1.0 was written in AmigaBasic, while
version 1.1 was written in Hisoft Basic and was much faster. For ZX DataType
I took the code from ZXscreen and converted it to C. It certainly is a hell
of a lot faster.

@ENDNODE

